          "body": "The psalm's capstone is verse 10: 'The fear of the Lord is the beginning of wisdom; a good understanding have all those who do His commandments; His praise endures forever.' This sentence is the Psalter's fullest statement of biblical epistemology, parallel to Proverbs 1:7 and Job 28:28. *Reshit* (beginning) does not merely mean the first step on a list — it means the foundational principle, the first cause, the generative source. Wisdom — *chokhmah*, skill in living rightly — does not begin with observation, reason, or tradition; it begins with the fear of the LORD. The connection to the rest of the psalm is not accidental. The psalmist has just spent nine verses observing the works, character, and covenant of the LORD. The only rational response to that observation — the only starting point for a life ordered correctly — is reverent awe. Fear (yirah) is the proper epistemic posture before a God whose works are great, whose righteousness endures forever, and whose name is holy and awesome. The final clause — 'His praise endures forever' — closes the frame: the psalmist's praise in verse 1 participates in an eternal doxology that will never end."
