        "excerpt": "I will give thanks to the Lord with all my heart, in the company of the upright and in the assembly.",
        "body": "The psalm opens not with a command to the congregation but with a personal declaration: *I will give thanks*. The Hebrew *yadah* is the standard word for thanksgiving-praise — the acknowledgment of God's goodness expressed in speech. But this is not a momentary feeling; it is a resolve of the will: 'I *will* give thanks.' The object is named before anything else is said: *to the LORD* — not to an experience of God, not to the idea of God, but to the covenant God of Israel, Yahweh.\n\nThe phrase 'with all my heart' (*bechol-levav*) is the Shema's own vocabulary (Deuteronomy 6:5 — 'you shall love the LORD your God with all your heart'). The psalmist is not introducing a new category; he is performing the Shema. To give thanks with all the heart is to love God with all the heart expressed as doxology. This is the psalm's first interpretive signal: what follows is not merely information about God but the overflow of a heart that has received and treasured that information.\n\nThe setting is simultaneously intimate and corporate. *Sod* (company, council) refers to the close circle of the upright — an intimate assembly of those who share the same moral orientation. *Edah* (assembly) is the larger gathered congregation. Both are in view at once. This is not the tension between private and public worship; it is the psalmist saying that genuine praise of the LORD belongs in both settings — it cannot be purely private (confined to the heart) or purely public (performed without heart). The two together constitute authentic doxology.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yadah* (give thanks) is the root of *todah* (the thank-offering); the verb carries a sacrificial echo — praise is an offering. *Levav* (heart) in Hebrew refers to the whole inner person — will, intellect, and affection together, not merely emotion. *Sod* (council, company) is used elsewhere of God's intimate counsel (Jeremiah 23:18, 22; Amos 3:7) — its use here for the assembly of the upright hints that the congregation of the upright is the place where God's own counsel is disclosed."
