        "title": "The works of God — studied, splendid, and morally charged",
        "range": "111:2-4",
        "excerpt": "Great are the works of the Lord; they are studied by all who delight in them. Splendid and majestic is His work, and His righteousness endures forever.",
        "body": "The psalm's central claim begins at verse 2: the works of the LORD are *great*. The Hebrew *gadol* is not primarily a superlative of size but of significance — the works are weighty, substantial, deserving of extended attention. And the psalm immediately names the appropriate response: *darash*, to study, to seek out carefully. The verb *darash* is used elsewhere for seeking God Himself (Deuteronomy 4:29; Psalm 34:4) and for careful investigation of the Torah (Ezra 7:10). It is not casual browsing. Those who delight (*chephets*) in the works of God are those who make them an object of sustained inquiry.\n\nThis is the psalm's implicit commentary on what biblical scholarship is for. Studying God's works — in creation, in history, in Scripture — is not an academic exercise detached from devotion; it is what *delight* looks like in practice. Jonathan Edwards saw the same connection: the mind that delights in God is the mind that wants to know more about Him, and the knowing feeds the delight in a recursive spiral. The inductive method applied to Scripture is the *darash* of verse 2.\n\nVerse 3 introduces beauty: His work is *hod* (splendor, the outward radiance of glory) and *hadar* (majesty, the weighty dignity of royalty). God's works are not merely powerful — they are beautiful. Aesthetic categories belong to the description of what God does. But verse 3 then pivots from aesthetics to ethics: 'His righteousness endures forever.' *Tsedaqah* is God's moral conformity to His own standard. The pairing of splendor/majesty with enduring righteousness is intentional: what makes God's works beautiful is not only their power or scale but their moral integrity. The beauty is grounded in the righteousness.\n\nVerse 4 introduces the psalm's doctrinal anchor. The wonders (*pala* — extraordinary acts, surpassing human ability) are made to be remembered. Memory is not accidental here; God has structured His acts so that they cannot be forgotten — He built the memorial into the event (feasts, festivals, commemorative stones). And then the psalmist names the character behind the wonders: 'The LORD is gracious (*channun*) and compassionate (*rachum*).' This is a direct citation of Exodus 34:6, the moment when God proclaimed His own name to Moses on Sinai after the golden calf. The psalmist is saying: the wonders of history are understandable only in light of the God who proclaimed His character at Sinai. The acts reveal the actor.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Darash* (studied/pondered) is the same verb used for the careful interpretation of Torah — its use here establishes the works of God as worthy of the same rigorous attention given to Scripture. *Pala* (wonders) specifically denotes acts that exceed human capacity — the lexical domain of miraculous, extraordinary divine intervention."
