        "title": "Covenant provision and conquest — the power of God made concrete",
        "range": "111:5-6",
        "excerpt": "He has given food to those who fear Him; He will remember His covenant forever. He has made known to His people the power of His works, in giving them the heritage of the nations.",
        "body": "Verse 5 brings the psalm from theological abstraction into material reality: *tereph* (food, prey, provision). The word can mean the meat torn by a predator — it is raw, concrete, physical sustenance. God gives food to those who fear Him. The reference is almost certainly to the wilderness provision — manna (Exodus 16), quail (Numbers 11), water from the rock (Exodus 17). The God who is gracious and compassionate (v.4) is also the God who feeds His people in the desert when there is nothing to eat.\n\nBut the food is not the end. It is the demonstration of a deeper reality: 'He will remember His covenant forever.' The covenant (*berit*) is the organizing framework of all the provision. God feeds Israel not because they are powerful or deserving but because He has bound Himself to them by oath. The food is a covenant act. This is the pattern of the entire OT: every act of divine provision is a re-enactment of covenant loyalty. When Jesus feeds five thousand in the wilderness (John 6), He is doing what Yahweh did — and the sign points to the bread of life that the covenant provision was always pointing toward.\n\nVerse 6 escalates the scale. God makes known 'the power (*koach*) of His works' not through private revelation but through historical event: 'in giving them the heritage of the nations.' This is the Conquest — the displacement of Canaan's inhabitants and the settlement of Israel in the land promised to Abraham (Genesis 15:18-21). The *nachalah* (inheritance, heritage) is the land itself as the embodied covenant promise. The nations did not surrender it willingly; God's power made it happen. The psalm is presenting the Conquest not as ethnic imperialism but as the covenant-keeping power of the God who always does what He says.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Zakhar* (remembers, v.5) is not passive recollection — in Hebrew, God's remembering is always active; when He remembers His covenant, He acts on it (cf. Genesis 8:1; Exodus 2:24). *Koach* (power, v.6) is the word for the kind of strength that accomplishes what ordinary means cannot."
