        "body": "Verses 7-8 pivot from what God has done in history to the moral character of both His acts and His precepts. 'The works of His hands are truth (*emet*) and justice (*mishpat*).' *Emet* is firmness, reliability, the quality of what holds — it is truth as ontological stability, not merely propositional accuracy. *Mishpat* is justice — the right ordering of relationships according to God's standard. Both words are predicated of the 'works of His hands': God's historical acts are not only powerful but morally right. They conform to His own standard of truth and justice.\n\nThe second half of verse 7 turns to the precepts (*piqqudim*): they are *aman* (trustworthy, faithful, firm). *Piqqudim* refers specifically to the statutes and ordinances of the Torah — the concrete instructions God has given His covenant people. Their trustworthiness is not derivative from human legislation or community consensus; it is grounded in the same character that makes God's works truth and justice. The precepts and the works both flow from the same source.\n\nVerse 8 then drives the temporal stake into the ground: 'They are upheld forever and ever' (*ad olam*, the double temporal expression). And the manner: 'performed in truth and uprightness (*yashar*).' *Yashar* (uprightness, straightness) is the moral quality of being uncrooked — God's precepts are not twisted, manipulated, or culturally adaptive. They are straight. This is an anti-relativist claim: the precepts do not shift with human consensus or historical context. They are performed in truth and uprightness, period, forever.\n\nThe theological payoff of verses 7-8 for the reader of the NT is significant. Jesus says in Matthew 5:17-18 that He did not come to abolish but to fulfill — and that not a jot or tittle of the Law would pass away until all is accomplished. The psalmist's 'forever and ever' is the OT foundation for Jesus's claim. The precepts endure because they are grounded in the character of a God who does not change.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Emet* (truth) and *aman* (trustworthy) share a root — the same root from which *amen* derives. To say 'amen' is to predicate the trustworthiness (*emet/aman*) of God's word back to Him. The psalm's vocabulary is liturgically generative."
