        "body": "Verse 9 is the psalm's narrative summit. Three declarations, each more doxological than the last. First: 'He has sent redemption (*pedut*) to His people.' *Pedut* is the noun form of *padah* — to ransom, to release by price. It appears only three times in the entire OT (here; Psalm 130:7; Isaiah 50:2), which signals its theological weight. The reference is the Exodus, but the word choice points beyond it: *pedut* is not merely rescue (which *yasha* would express) but ransom — release from bondage through the payment of a price. The Exodus involved exactly this: the Lord 'bought' Israel out of Egypt through the plagues and the death of the firstborn, and the blood of the Passover lamb was the sign of that purchase.\n\nPeter Davids notes in his discussion of ransom terminology that the NT writers deliberately reach back to exactly this vocabulary when describing the cross — *lutron* (ransom, Mark 10:45), *antilutron* (1 Timothy 2:6), *agorazo* (bought with a price, 1 Corinthians 6:20; 7:23). The psalmist's *pedut* is on a canonical trajectory that reaches its terminus in the cross of Christ, the one who 'has sent redemption to His people' in the most ultimate and final sense. The Exodus was a type; the cross was the antitype.\n\nSecond: 'He has ordained His covenant forever.' The verb *tsavah* (ordained, commanded) is strong — it is the word for an authoritative decree. The covenant is not a suggestion or a provisional arrangement; it is an eternal decree of God. The combination with *olam* (forever) echoes the Abrahamic covenant of Genesis 17:7 ('I will establish My covenant between Me and you and your descendants after you throughout their generations for an everlasting covenant') and the Davidic covenant of 2 Samuel 7:16 ('Your house and your kingdom shall endure before Me forever'). The psalm is conscious of the full sweep of covenant history.\n\nThird: 'Holy and awesome is His name.' Having narrated the acts of the LORD across eight verses, the psalmist arrives at the only adequate summary: the name — which in Hebrew thought encapsulates the person and character — is *qadosh* (holy, set apart, wholly other) and *yare* (awesome, fear-inducing). The acts disclosed the name; the name now stands as the psalm's doxological summit before the wisdom capstone of verse 10.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Pedut* (redemption) — noun form appearing only three times in the OT. The cognate verb *padah* is used in Exodus 13:13-15 of the redemption of the firstborn, the very mechanism the Passover makes concrete. *Qadosh* (holy) is the word of radical divine otherness — the seraphim of Isaiah 6:3 predicate it of the LORD three times (*qadosh qadosh qadosh*) to mark its superlative force."
