        "excerpt": "The fear of the Lord is the beginning of wisdom; a good understanding have all those who do His commandments; His praise endures forever.",
        "body": "Verse 10 is the psalm's capstone and one of the most important single verses in the OT. 'The fear of the LORD is the *reshit* (beginning, first principle) of wisdom (*chokhmah*).' The parallel in Proverbs 1:7 ('The fear of the LORD is the beginning of knowledge') and Job 28:28 ('the fear of the Lord — that is wisdom') shows that this is not an isolated aphorism but the unanimous verdict of Israel's wisdom tradition. *Reshit* means not merely the first chronological step but the foundational principle — the archē, the source, the generative starting point. All wisdom — practical, moral, intellectual — has its root in the fear of the LORD.\n\nThe fear of the LORD (*yirat Yahweh*) is not servile terror. It is the reverent awe that perceives God correctly: as great, as morally holy, as the one whose name is awesome (v.9). It is the epistemic posture of the creature before the Creator — the acknowledgment that God is the referent, the standard, and the source of all reality. Without it, human knowing is unmoored. With it, 'a good understanding (*sekhel tov*) have all those who do His commandments.' The connection between fearing God and doing His commandments is not moralistic; it is ontological. Obedience is the outworking of genuinely perceiving who God is. If you actually see the LORD as the psalm has described Him across nine verses, you obey — because obedience is the rational response to such a God.\n\nThe final clause — 'His praise endures forever (*ad*)' — closes the literary frame that opened at verse 1 ('I will give thanks to the LORD'). The psalmist's personal vow of praise in verse 1 is now set against an eternal horizon: the praise of the LORD does not end with this psalm, this assembly, or this psalmist. It is an eternal reality — what Revelation 4-5 depicts as the ceaseless doxology of every creature in heaven and on earth. The psalmist's 'I will give thanks' participates in something larger than itself. This is the ultimate dignity of the worshipper: to join a chorus that will never fall silent.\n\nThe canonical trajectory of verse 10 runs through the NT in several directions. James 1:5 promises wisdom to those who ask God in faith — but that wisdom is available precisely because they are in relationship with the God whose character Psalm 111 has just narrated. The NT's repeated call to 'fear God' (1 Peter 2:17; Revelation 14:7) is not a retreat to servile terror but a re-anchoring of human knowing and living in the same referent the psalmist names: the holy and awesome God whose works are great, whose covenant is eternal, and whose redemption has been sent to His people — most finally in the person of His Son.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Reshit* (beginning) is the same word as Genesis 1:1 ('In the beginning God created') — the psalm is claiming that the same principle that governs creation governs epistemology: both begin with God. *Sekhel tov* (good understanding) — *sekhel* is practical prudence, the kind of discernment that navigates life well, not merely academic intelligence."
